IBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

If you watch the highlights of last week=E2=80=99s auction for the stolen r=
uby slippers that Judy Garland wore in The Wizard of Oz, it=E2=80=99s hard =
not to be startled by the raucous bidding. At one point, the auctioneer wav=
es off a $4.8 million bid that=E2=80=99s just been overrun by two other com=
peting bids with an angry, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve got $4.9, it wouldn=E2=80=
=99t have mattered.=E2=80=9D And that was just the beginning of the run. Th=
ere were still 10 bidders above $5 million, eventually winnowing down to th=
e final bid of $28 million. The buyer will pay an astounding $32.5 million =
with fees.

The sale of the =E2=80=9Cno place like home=E2=80=9D shoes, run by Heritage=
 Auctions, was a milestone for many reasons. With the first installment of =
Wicked in theaters, L. Frank Baum=E2=80=99s fictional world is more cultura=
lly relevant than ever; Judy
Garland remains a talisman of the tragic-but-glamorous Hollywood of the 20t=
h century; and Dorothy Gale=E2=80=99s Oz odyssey remains a powerful fable o=
f self-acceptance and healing. But most of all, the sale puts the market fo=
r Hollywood memorabilia permanently on the map.

