NEWS/B32797622.409127523;dc_trk_aid=3D601046988;dc_trk_cid=3D226429236;dc_l=
at=3D;dc_rdid=3D;tag_for_child_directed_treatment=3D;tfua=3D;ltd=3D;dc_tdv=
=3D1?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F15%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Joseph Maddalena, Heritage=E2=80=99s head of its popular culture categories=
, said afterward that the sale was the culmination of his 40 years=E2=80=99=
 experience in the business=E2=80=94longer if you count his parents=E2=80=
=99 experience with Hollywood memorabilia. Just a few weeks ago, he held a =
Game of Thrones auction that made $21 million. But the ruby slippers were, =
he told me, =E2=80=9Cthe most important objects in entertainment.=E2=80=9D =
Friends who called to congratulate him all said the same thing: =E2=80=9CYo=
u finally got there.=E2=80=9D

A Token in the Legend Meter

There=E2=80=99s another piece to the slippers=E2=80=99 allure, of course: T=
hey were stolen almost 20 years ago. A similar theft is also at the heart o=
f the global celebrity of the Mona Lisa. Most people who crowd into the Lou=
vre museum to view that painting don=E2=80=99t know that La Joconde, as the=
 French call it, spent centuries in relative obscurity before it was stolen=
 by an Italian patriot in 1911, in the aftermath of which a French newspape=
r war transformed the painting into one of the most famous objects in the w=
orld.

It took two years to recover the Mona Lisa and return it to France. Recover=
ing Dorothy=E2=80=99s ruby slippers took a bit longer. The shoes, along wit=
h the rest of MGM=E2=80=99s costume archive, some 350,000 items, had been l=
anguishing in storage when, after the studio was sold to Kirk Kerkorian in =
1969, costume
designer Kent Warner was given the task of searching the trove for items th=
at could be sold at auction. Warner found several pairs of the ruby slipper=
s in the mountain of dross, one of which was sold in the subsequent auction=
 for $15,000. (That pair eventually ended up in the Smithsonian, where the =
foot traffic in front of the vitrine regularly makes the carpet threadbare.=
) Warner quietly sold another pair he=E2=80=99d found to a collector named =
Michael Shaw, who toured them for years until, while spending a summer on d=
isplay at the Judy Garland Museum in her birthplace, Grand Rapids, Minnesot=
a, the slippers were stolen.

For 13 years, the mystery of who had stolen the ruby slippers and why anima=
ted the world of pop culture memorabilia and fed into the broader fascinati=
on with Garland=E2=80=99s tragic life. There=E2=80=99s even a podcast ( htt=
ps://open.spotify.com/show/0M0kdqyMz7sfCXp2w4dvKY?si=3D4048239265f245df&utm=
_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F15%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+=
Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) devoted to the search. Earli=
er this year, the F.B.I. charged ( https://www.pbs.org/newshour/arts/dying-=
thief-who-stole-ruby-slippers-from-the-judy-garland-museum-in-2005-gets-no-=
prison-time?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F15%2F24%29&utm_=
content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_ac=
tion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) the second of=
 two men in connection with the theft. The thieves didn=E2=80=99t appreciat=
e the value of the famous footwear, but at least they
took good care of the slippers while they were in their possession.

All of that lore, mystery, and anticipation fueled last week=E2=80=99s auct=
ion, driving the final sale
price to nearly $30 million above the estimate. Before the sale, Maddalena =
toured the shoes around the world to show them off in Tokyo, London, and Ne=
w York. He believes that, like art, Hollywood artifacts are cultural icons.=
 =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s their art,=E2=80=9D he said of die-hard collectors l=
ike Shaw.

Maddalena also believes the market for these cultural artifacts is the same=
 as the art market, despite their apparent differences. Maddalena described=
 the art market as =E2=80=9Cpreconditioned to comparative analysis.=E2=80=
=9D But the memorabilia market is just beginning to get its data points. A =
huge new high price in the category will likely raise other prices in relat=
ion. Of course, we won=E2=80=99t know which objects will be priced off the =
ruby slippers until they=E2=80=99re sold. Until then, Maddalena is just hap=
py that =E2=80=9Cthese things are getting their due,=E2=80=9D and he hopes =
that the ultimate value of the shoes is =E2=80=9Cthe wonderful nostalgic jo=
urney=E2=80=9D they take you on.

That=E2=80=99s it for today. More on Tuesday,
