x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">If you watch the hi=
ghlights of last week=E2=80=99s auction for the stolen ruby slippers that <=
b>Judy Garland</b> wore in <i>The</i> <i>Wizard of Oz</i>, it=E2=80=99s har=
d not to be startled by the raucous bidding. At one point, the auctioneer w=
aves off a $4.8 million bid that=E2=80=99s just been overrun by two other c=
ompeting bids with an angry, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve got $4.9, it wouldn=E2=
=80=99t have mattered.=E2=80=9D And that was just the <i>beginning</i> of t=
he run. There were still 10 bidders above $5 million, eventually winnowing =
down to the final bid of $28 million. The buyer will pay an astounding $32.=
5 million with fees.<br/><br/>The sale of the =E2=80=9Cno place like home=
=E2=80=9D shoes, run by Heritage Auctions, was a milestone for many reasons=
=2E With the first installment of <i>Wi=
cked</i> in theaters, <b>L. Frank</b>=20=
<b>Baum</b>=E2=80=99s fictional world is more culturally relevant than ever=
; Judy
Garland remains a talisman of the tragic-but-glamorous Hollywood of the 20t=
h century; and Dorothy Gale=E2=80=99s Oz odyssey remains a powerful fable o=
f self-acceptance and healing. But most of all, the sale puts the market fo=
r Hollywood memorabilia permanently on the map. <br/></td>
