4ea3b30cd0a1e23a3eb413e85913f216a995935c7" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-deco=
ration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">charged</a></u> the second of t=
wo men in connection with the theft. The thieves didn=E2=80=99t appreciate =
the value of the famous footwear, but at least they took good care of the s=
lippers while they were in their possession.<br/><br/>All of that lore, mys=
tery, and anticipation fueled last week=E2=80=99s auction, driving the fina=
l sale
price to nearly $30 million above the estimate. Before the sale, Maddalena =
toured the shoes around the world to show them off in Tokyo, London, and Ne=
w York. He believes that, like art, Hollywood artifacts are cultural icons.=
 =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s <i>their</i> art,=E2=80=9D he said of die-hard colle=
ctors like Shaw.<br/><br/>Maddalena also believes the market for these cult=
ural artifacts is the same as the art market, despite their apparent differ=
ences. Maddalena described the art market as =E2=80=9Cpreconditioned to com=
parative analysis.=E2=80=9D But the memorabilia market is just beginning to=
 get its data points. A huge new high price in the category will likely rai=
se other prices in relation. Of course, we won=E2=80=99t know which objects=
 will be priced off the ruby slippers until they=E2=80=99re sold. Until the=
n, Maddalena is just happy that =E2=80=9Cthese things are getting their due=
,=E2=80=9D and he hopes that the ultimate value of the shoes is =E2=80=9Cth=
e wonderful nostalgic journey=E2=80=9D they take you on. <br/></td>
